ce:section.ce:para:
The synthesis of MNC/CNM hybrids can take different pathways depending on the properties of the nanoclusters (nature of the metal, size, and surface chemistry), the type of carbon material, and the desired properties and intended application for the resulting hybrid (Scheme 5
                        ). The most common methods can be broadly subdivided into: (i) mixing of dispersions with non-covalent interactions; (ii) mixing of dispersions with covalent bonding; (iii) in situ synthesis and (iv) in silico methods. The first method involves the separate production of the starting materials, followed by mixing of the respective individual dispersions to form the hybrid via non-covalent interactions, such as electrostatic interactions, hydrogen bonds, or π-π stacking. The second one implies the separate production of both materials and formation of covalent bonds between them via coupling reactions. The most widespread coupling reaction involves the activation of carboxylic acids with 1-ethyl-3-(−3-dimethylaminopropyl) carbodiimide hydrochloride (EDAC) to react with sulfo-N-hydroxysuccinimide (sulfo-NHS) that covalent binds with -NH2 functional groups to form an amide linkage (see Scheme 6
                        ). In the third method, in situ synthesis, one of the nanomaterials, either MNC or CNM, is formed in situ aided by the presence of the other. This strategy has been particularly popular to prepare MNC/Cdots hybrids, whereby the Cdots act as reducing agents for the metal ion thus leading to the production of MNCs. Finally, in silico methods have also been employed to elucidate the formation and properties of hybrids, including molecular dynamics (MD) simulations and other computational tools. In the following sections (4.2–4.4), the preparation methods are discussed in more detail with respect to the nature of the MNC and type of CNM, from 0D (e.g. Cdots), through 1D (CNTs) to 2D (e.g. graphene and GO nanosheets).

Hg2+ is by far the predominant analyte probed by MNC/CNM hybrids. One of the first examples employed two different types of AuNCs supported on GO-NH3
                           + [170]. After this early report, the sensing of Hg2+has been focused on the use of MNC/Cdot hybrids [24,125,136,143,144,148,152]. The luminescence of AuNCs is quenched by Hg2+ due to the formation of metallophilic Hg2+-Au+ interactions, while the luminescence of the Cdots remains unchanged. Typically, the change in the relative intensity of the dual emission of AuNCs/Cdots hybrid results in a change of color under UV lamp, from pink to blue, dependent on the concentration of Hg2+ [24]. A colorimetric sensor was built by immobilization of the nanohybrid in a cellulose acetate filter that responded to the presence of Hg2+ in real water samples [24]. This approach was extended to Cr6+ sensing [113], whereby the blue fluorescence emission of Cdots was quenched by Cr6+, while the BSA-AuNCs luminescence remained constant (Fig. 8
                           ). The net effect was a color change from pink to red with increasing concentration of Cr6+(Fig. 8 I). The quenching of the Cdots luminescence by Cr6+ was attributed to IFE upon complexation of Cr6+ with functional groups at the surface of the Cdots. Considering the selective responses of the emission of AuNCs by Hg2+ and of the emission of Cdots by Cr6+, it was possible to achieve separate and/or simultaneous Hg2+ and Cr6+ detection. The simultaneous detection resulted in the disappearance of the color since both the Cdots (blue) and AuNCs (red) emissions were quenched (Fig. 8 III).
